<subSubSection id="9F0B4B7F7D8FC199777E0F0C5E28C62A" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A62C9060876CC919E5C545F4361A242A" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C791269202A1DD6999B9C89529E6E05" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicName id="AB5DAED5445AD64F8FCC686C78BC480D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum nigrum" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigrum">
<emphasis id="53BDE1C995FBC8AC753BB887266DC79F" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Solanum nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably introduced in temperate North America; populations on the eastern seaboard best match European populations in overall morphology. Populations from the western coast (e.g., British Colombia) are morphologically more similar to Eurasian plants and it is possible that they are the result either of introductions from that region over the Pacific or are relictual native plants that came across the Bering Straits during warm periods in the Quaternary (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="28744732DDD882A848F1204800ACFD77" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/17550870802328660" author="DeChaine, E" journalOrPublisher="Plant Ecology &amp; Diversity" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" pagination="197 - 207" refId="B65" refString="DeChaine, E, 2008. A bridge or a barrier? Beringia's influence on the distribution and diversity of tundra plants. Plant Ecology &amp; Diversity 1 (2): 197 - 207, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/17550870802328660" title="A bridge or a barrier? Beringia's influence on the distribution and diversity of tundra plants." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/17550870802328660" volume="1" year="2008">DeChaine 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5245BB1BB1DCE6C0275CF6A0EB28350A" author="Ickert-Bond, SM" journalOrPublisher="Alaska Park Science" pageId="113" pageNumber="114" pagination="26 - 32" refId="B114" refString="Ickert-Bond, SM, Murray, DF, DeChaine, E, 2009. Contrasting patterns of plant distribution in Beringia. Alaska Park Science 8 (2): 26 - 32" title="Contrasting patterns of plant distribution in Beringia." volume="8" year="2009">Ickert-Bond et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Molecular population genetic analysis of these populations has not been done but should shed some light on the status of 
<taxonomicName id="C03642CAB7FD31D560DB54A12EA2A2D5" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. nigrum" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="nigrum">
<emphasis id="696B3852F753F4439CE8CC7E32AFED57" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in North America.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0E33BD54EEF888E65682344FEC87A5A3" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicName id="67B8A2E8A69654A0B45462E14765FECD" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum nigrum" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigrum">
<emphasis id="862938D9F1A38FF36E9286DAD069FF7D" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Solanum nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other North American species (e.g., 
<emphasis id="9A0E4746EA0B3DD9DAA0653A9CAE20A0" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicName id="B56C0EC9E6D1C39741D4C06669AF52BC" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. americanum" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="americanum">S. americanum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="AC8B82BD5793B4E213C1F1D4837011CF" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. douglasii" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="douglasii">S. douglasii</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6CA38F29CD0196954192CFC19AB0BBCA" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. emulans" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="emulans">
<emphasis id="66F0AD9B6B2240DB1C9271A97D5F7CCA" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. emulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="F46BBA0C80321B6DF696C8000DE60878" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. interius" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="interius">
<emphasis id="B2C846DEBC3F02CD2B840AFC20512E64" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. interius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A6BD0621EEB229596D76EA7613E248B6" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. nigrescens" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis id="7BAD9D4E9821C4A905B3DAC12EE33E63" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in the character combination of thicker peduncles and pedicels, larger seeds and fruits lacking stone cells. It has longer anthers (2.5-3 mm) than 
<taxonomicName id="00CEB0584A818F8F8F5F22BDE6A56D9E" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. emulans" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="emulans">
<emphasis id="C94DD47E15010449D0FD7EFE2018484C" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. emulans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="60909AA4497D6B38F5EDF5A748277CBF" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. americanum" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="americanum">
<emphasis id="477361E11A9E00676495DEE5EFE01BB6" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. americanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both of which have tiny anthers ca. 1.5 mm long. Like 
<taxonomicName id="FA521B1F634661B04EC459815022786C" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. nigrescens" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis id="6CC4D962DBD1A7C4D9E2E70E5FC5340D" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it has inflorescences with the flowers spaced along the rhachis, but 
<taxonomicName id="5C8D2678CC9717585FD88042B1BD031C" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. nigrescens" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis id="2A830EFF811E65553665EAAF78A3DD5D" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. nigrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has prominent stone cells in the berries and smaller seeds. 
<taxonomicName id="20E80CC2BF0C8A042B78AA78E83844E1" authorityName="Rydb., Bull. Torrey Bot. Club 31: 641. 1905 [&quot;" authorityYear="1904" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum interius" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="interius">
<emphasis id="A5530D5F8442496AAE9929D9CD538622" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Solanum interius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has similarly large seeds but has fewer flowers per inflorescence and distinctive basal flower pedicel position (articulation above the join with the rhachis).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A9703F8DDC6435F0F2F95A1CF98CD9F4" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">Michael Nee (pers. comm.) has observed its spread and increase in the New York City area over the last decade; it is possible that more collections will be made throughout North America in the coming years.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F257BCC399BACFF197E4D12643A4BC3E" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">
For typification details of the many synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="303889D0A54162B9F5F1798D686D7352" family="Verbenaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. nigrum" order="Solanales" pageId="75" pageNumber="76" rank="species" species="nigrum">
<emphasis id="389998E22DD2233A2EA9F5463D1F9D6E" italics="true" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">S. nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation id="8EF9ABF96B1B8F0499BE4009F30AFBED" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" author="Saerkinen, T" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" pagination="1 - 223" refId="B204" refString="Saerkinen, T, Poczai, P, Barboza, GE, van der Weerden, GM, Baden, M, Knapp, S, 2018. A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae). PhytoKeys 106: 1 - 223, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" title="A revision of the Old World black nightshades (Morelloid clade of Solanum L., Solanaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/phytokeys.106.21991" volume="106" year="2018">
<normalizedToken id="7C6EAD69D611E4648EC658BA6BE923F3" originalValue="Särkinen">Saerkinen</normalizedToken>
et al. (2018)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
